</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub59.ezboard.com/bguild75784.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brokenfang>Brokenfang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cons Threateningly </span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#333333>(11/7/02 4:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub59.ezboard.com/fguild75784frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=80.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Here comes the NERF STICK !!!! (tm)</span><hr size=1> I realize this is totally dredging up a dead horse.  But I figure since it's not 'in the heat of the moment' anymore, I can ask what may have once been a controversial question without people getting wriled with thier answers.<br>
<br>
I saw a good number of people on this board and others loving the MB change.  Claiming that it was evil and overpowered and all other kinds of good stuff.  Now, I'm probably taking this too much to heart, being a wizard that did have manaburn (I say did, I didn't purchase it again when the points were refunded) but I have to ask why?<br>
<br>
Now, I know stories abound with raids KS'd by manaburning wizards.  Hell, I was even accused of being one of those wizards by a certain VS raid one night when a) I had been in the same zone for about 4 hours grinding (and it wasn't Karnors) and b) I was still 2 points away from even getting Manaburn.  So it showed me very clearly people can and are very quick to point fingers at things they don't understand.<br>
<br>
I'll be honost here, yes, after getting manaburn I did group with other wizards from time to time and burn dragons.  I'll even be direct and say I know for certain that some of them were only in it to line thier pockets.  But do you not realize that this change hurt smaller guilds more then it actually hurt the wizards it directly effected?  <br>
<br>
I made a grand total of 0pp from the loot I obtained from burning things.  I can also say without a doubt that we never stepped on anyone elses toes.  At least for the burns I was part of when I got in I made sure to check the zone to see if a force capable of killing a dragon was around.  And several times sent direct tells to other people asking if they were since numbers were on the border and they might just be waiting for a few more.  Every kill was announced in /ooc and /shout before the dragon was pulled.  Never once did I see a response saying that the mob was being prepped for.<br>
<br>
My sole reason for obtaining manaburn was to help get some hard to find spells and possibly some epic pieces into my guild.  There's really nothing I want more from this game right now then to get my hands on a white dragon scale for our guilds ranking bard to finish her epic.  The same piece that's been holding her up for months on end now.  I held a total of 1 item I got to loot for my personal gain.  It was an RBB.  I also made it very clear that I was holding it until I got a copy of sunstrike.  And that if I was able to obtain the spell without having to sell/trade the RBB then it would be given freely to a member of the guild.  Unfortunately, I did end up trading the RBB, to a ranger, for Sunstrike.<br>
<br>
Now, you can say that it was the few bad apples that were in it for themselves that ruined it for the rest of us.  But I ask you, did it really change anything?  Single groups were able to farm kunark dragons before manaburn existed, and can still continue to do so now.  Now, you can say that there's risk involved for them to do it, where there was none for the wizard.  But realisticly, there isn't.  If they're farming it with one group, they're well enough along that there really isn't any true risk involved to them, it just takes a little longer to accomplish.  Nothing's really changed on that aspect, other then who's doing it.<br>
<br>
Now, to totally disregard the 'roving band of wizards' arguement for a moment and focus on teh skill itself.  Do you realize that manaburn was based ona completly random modifier? I couldn't look at my mana and say &quot;Oh, I have about 3500 mana I'm going to unload a 7k hit&quot;  And even under the best of conditions.  There was never a time that I would do more damage unloading MB then if I had used that mana to nuke traditionally.  Aslo, using MB leaves a wizard completly out of mana.  If I ever had a mob beat on me after using a burn, even a little green con, I would be completly defenseless to even so much as root it and back off or gate out.  We got left nothing to defend ourselves with, at all.<br>
<br>
The only real use MB had on large hitpoint mobs was a chance for some agro free damage at the start of a battle.  Used in conjunction with modrods and other mana regen buffs/songs A wizard could open early with manaburn, which would really do next to nothing against the mobs total hp.  And then rod/med back up to a reasonable mana pool when it was time to start nuking down.  With the alteration to mod rods it makes this use on high hitpoint mobs completly useless.  I can either burn early and set it out the majority of the fight, maybe getting a couple nukes in at the end.  Or I can nuke the way I should be and unload at the end.  But wait, I won't have any mana left near the end, so it would be useless to waste the burn.<br>
<br>
Guess I just felt the need to explain a little bit how MB worked and where it was actually practicle.  I'm still very interested in hearing exactly why people thought MB was overpowered.  I know the stories run rampant.  But I'm interested in actual first hand accounts.  Not the stories from a friend of a friend of a friend...<br>
<br>
<br>
And Just for Dief..... <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.carpenocturnus.com/Brokenfang.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
